<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-361-644  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 361 644.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  June 1989 v14 n6 p275(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Know thy viral enemy: the viruses you're most likely to meet.andO;(computer viruses) (includes related articles on 'Two otherviruses' and 'Two Mac viruses.')andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Greenberg, Ross M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A great deal of research is underway to devise ways of diagnosingand stopping computer viruses before they infiltrate networks andcause irreparable damage.andP;  Many viruses have been identified butsix PC-based viruses are the most prevalent.andP;  These are discussedin detail along with two lesser-known viruses and twoMacintosh-based viruses.andP;  Viruses infect systems mainly through acontaminated floppy disk.andP;  This explains why many systems areinfected through the introduction of shareware, though evenshrink-wrapped software is not immune.andP;  The various strains ofcomputer viruses are becoming more and more potent andsophisticated.andP;  Viruses are serious, potentially expensive anddisastrous in terms of damaged or destroyed data or hardware.andO;Microcomputers must be protected through use of common sense andas many preventive measures as possible.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer virusesDesignPreventive MaintenanceImplementationNetworksSecurity.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   A virus infecting a system. (chart)An impossible dilemma. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>